      "text": "[[Sri Lanka]] has the oldest radio station in Asia (world's second oldest). The station was known as [[Radio Ceylon]]. It developed into one of the finest broadcasting institutions in the world. It is now known as the [[Sri Lanka Broadcasting Corporation]]. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "876b9c808dedf107",
      "text": "Sri Lanka created [[broadcasting]] history in Asia when broadcasting was started in Ceylon by the Telegraph Department in 1923 on an experimental footing, just three years after the inauguration of broadcasting in Europe. Gramophone music was broadcast from a tiny room in the Central Telegraph Office with the aid of a small transmitter built by the Telegraph Department engineers from the radio equipment of a captured German submarine -\n [http://www.flonnet.com/fl2301/stories/20060127001908700.htm flonnet.com] "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7c20740b3af0844b",
      "text": "This broadcasting experiment was successful; barely three years later, on December 16, 1925, a regular broadcasting service came to be instituted. Edward Harper who came to [[Ceylon]] as Chief Engineer of the Telegraph Office in 1921, was the first person to actively promote broadcasting in Ceylon. [[Sri Lanka]] occupies an important place in the history of broadcasting with broadcasting services inaugurated just three years after the launch of the [[BBC]] in the United Kingdom. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c8a2887ed5978c43",
      "text": "Edward Harper ([[Edward Harper (engineer)]]) launched the first experimental broadcast as well as founding the Ceylon Wireless Club, together with British and Ceylonese radio enthusiasts on the island. Edward Harper has been dubbed ' the Father of Broadcasting in Ceylon,' because of his pioneering efforts, his skill and his determination to succeed. Edward Harper and his fellow Ceylonese radio enthusiasts, made it happen."
